ethical issues such as the anonymity of informants and the place of Western ethnomusicologists in countries outside the West. Drawn from interviews conducted from 2007 through 2009 with Burmese composers, performers, producers, concert promoters, journalists, recording engineers, radio station employees, music teachers, and censors in Yangon -- Burma's largest city and the locus of all pop music production -- Burma's Pop Music Industry represents a significant contribution both to popular music studies and to Southeast Asian studies. Heather MacLachlan is Assistant Professor of Music, University of Dayton.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMusic tradezBurma. 0aPopular musicxCensorshipzBurma. 0aPopular musicxHistory and criticismzBurma. 0aPopular musicxSocial aspectszBurma. 4aAsian Studies. 4aFilm & Theatre. 4aModern History. 4aMusic. 7aMUSIC / Ethnomusicology.2bisacsh  aBurma.  aBurmese Composers.  aConcert Promoters.  aEthical Issues.  aEthnomusicologists.  aHeather MacLachlan.  aJournalists.  aMusic Industry.  aMusical Artists.  aPerformers.  aPop Music Industry.  aRadio Station.  aRecording Engineers.  aSocial and Political Context.  aSoutheast Asian Country.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781580467377?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781580467377423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781580467377/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles